  "prompt": "Is divorce in India one-sided?",
  "response": "Divorce in India is not one-sided. The legal system allows both men and women to file for divorce under various grounds, as specified in different personal laws. These laws include the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955; Special Marriage Act, 1954; Indian Divorce Act, 1869; and the Muslim Personal Law, among others. \n\nUnder these laws, both spouses have the right to initiate divorce proceedings. Grounds for divorce can include cruelty, adultery, desertion, conversion to another religion, mental disorder, communicable diseases, and mutual consent, among others.\n\nIndia also recognizes mutual consent divorces, where both parties agree to separate amicably. This process tends to be quicker and less contentious compared to a contested divorce, where one party files for divorce and the other may oppose it.\n\nIt's worth noting that societal attitudes and cultural norms can influence the experiences of individuals seeking divorce, and these factors may sometimes result in perceived biases or difficulties for one party. However, legally, both parties have the right to seek divorce.",
